text:
\begin{equation}
V_{\rm rec} \sim V_{\rm A} M_{\rm A}^{2},
\end{equation}

nexttext:
and angular brackets denote averaging along the $z$ direction
(along the largest side of the current sheet,
i.e., perpendicular to the electric current, see \Fig{rec}).
So the method of the determining $V_{\rm rec}$
in numerical simulations can be as following:

(i) to find the region with the current sheet that is separated magnetic field of the
opposite polarities;

(ii) to use the different instants of
the formation of the current layer and to determine the value of $V_{\rm rec}$,
the length of the current layer, $L_z$, the Alfv\'en speed $V_{\rm A}$
in these instants;

(iii) to determine $S^{-1/2}$ and $M_{\rm A}^2=u_{\rm rms}^2/V_{\rm A}^2$,
and compare these quantities with $V_{\rm rec}/V_{\rm A}$
obtained from DNS.

