Results of calculation of the rate of the reconnection, $V_{\rm rec}$ are
presented in \Tab{Tab2}.
To determine the reconnection rate, we measure both, the velocity $V_{\rm E}$
using Equation \ref{recE} and the incoming velocity $V_{\rm in}$
in the vicinity of the current sheet (in the case of 2D flow it is in $y$
direction).
We normalize the velocities by the mean value of $V_{\rm A}$
because the speed $V_{\rm A}$ varies with time (see \Fig{pt}).
In this section, in order to be able to compare the results of
the different runs, we use $(t-t_{rec})/\tautd$ for the normalized time where,
$t_{rec}$ is the time when the reconnection starts for each individual Run.
\Fig{pt}  presents the time evolution of the different quantities
in three separate panels ($|\langle\BB \rangle|$ (solid line), and
$|\langle\EE \rangle|$ (dotted line) in the upper panel,
$V_{\rm A}/\langle V_{\rm A} \rangle$ (stars), and
$u_{\rm rms}/\langle \urms \rangle$ (circles) in the middle panel, and finally
$V_{\rm in}/\langle V_{\rm in} \rangle$ (stars),
and $l_{\rm z}k_{1}$ (triangles) in the lower panel).
The different colors represent  different values of
$\Rm$ ($\Rm=50$ (black), $\Rm=130$ (blue), and $\Rm=260$ (red)).
One can see that, $\urms/\langle \urms \rangle$ do not change strongly with time
and $V_{\rm A}\langle V_{\rm A} \rangle$ changes when $\Rm$ is smaller
($\Rm=50$).
This implies that the major change in $S$ comes from the change in
the length of the current sheet (see the lower panel of \Fig{pt}).

