To check which regime of magnetic reconnection is appropriate,
we plot in \Fig{vrecvas} $V_{\rm E}$ and
$V_{\rm in}$ as a function of $S$.
We also plot $S^{-1/2}$ curve (hereafter SP curve) to compare it
with our data.
Within large scatter, our data points are consistent
with the SP theory \citep{P57,S69,P94} for
small values of $S < 10^4$ but as we move to larger values of $S>10^4$,
the data points strongly differ from the SP curve,
but are consistent with the results of numerical simulations
for turbulent regime of reconnection \citep{LUS09,HB10,LSS12,B13},
where the reconnection rate is nearly independent of $S$.
Indeed, by comparing the curves for different values of magnetic Reynolds numbers,
$\Rm=50, 130, 260$, it is clear that the difference between
data points and the SP curve increases as Reynolds number increase.
The reason is that by increasing $\Rm$,
the system deviates strongly from the laminar regime and
does not follow the SP model anymore.
In this case we observe the turbulent regime of reconnection.

In \Fig{vrecvas_t}, we show the time dependency
of reconnection rate.
For $\Rm=50$, the reconnection rate does not change strongly,
but for higher values of $\Rm$, it changes with time.
Finally \Figs{vrecvas}{vrecvas_t} show that,
the reconnection rates obtained from the measurements of $V_{\rm in}$
and $V_{\rm E}$ are similar and
nearly independent of $S$.

