\section{Conclusions}

In the present paper, we have extended the result of \cite{Mit14} to
higher magnetic Reynolds number and have investigated the effects
of rotation at different Coriolis numbers.
Our results demonstrate that in the two-layer model,
with helical forcing at the bottom and non-helical forcing at the top,
sharp bipolar spots form at the surface, expand and then
develops stripy structures.
The observed effects are similar for different values of $\Rm$ and $\Co$.
In our present simulations, for $\Co$ as large as 1.4, we still observe
the formation of the intense bipolar structures.
This value is significantly larger than what was previously obtained
in the studies of the magnetic flux concentration in rotating flows
in turbulence with an imposed weak magnetic field.
We recall that the combined action of rotation and stratification causes
the generation of kinetic helicity \citep{KR80,KR03,Jabbari14}.
This explains why for the models with stratification and fast rotation,
one still observes the formation of bipolar structures.
Although there are dynamo-generated magnetic fields in our simulations, which
is more realistic compared to several previous models with
an imposed magnetic field, we still
observe evidence for downflows at the locations
of magnetic structure formation,
similar to \cite{BGJKR14}, \cite{Mit14}, and \cite{Jabbari15}.
In the present work, we have also investigated the effects of
varying the scale separation ratio ($\kf/k_{1}$).
Contrary to earlier studies of NEMPI, for $\kf/k_{1}$ as small as
five, bipolar magnetic structures are still formed.

What is surprising is the long lifetime of the resulting bipolar regions,
which exceeds several turbulent diffusion times.
Clearly, turbulent diffusion destroys sharp structures.
We suggest that the main reason that these intense magnetic structures survive longer
is due to a magnetic reconnection phenomenon occurring
in the vicinity of the current sheet that forms between opposite magnetic polarities.
We have determined the reconnection rate for a range of different parameters
and have shown that for high Lundquist numbers, $S>10^4$,
the measured reconnection rate is nearly independent of $S$.
This result is in disagreement with the classical Sweet-Parker reconnection model
\citep{P57,S69,P94},
but consistent with recent numerical simulations in a turbulent regime of
reconnection performed by other groups \citep{LUS09,HB10,LSS12,B13}.
The measured reconnection rate is independent of the squared Alfv\'en Mach
number, $M_{\rm A}^2$, which is inconsistent with \cite{LV99}.

Finally, we comment on the mechanism behind
the formation of the bipolar structures and its relation to NEMPI.
In both, our two-layer model with dynamo-generated magnetic field
and in turbulent systems with an imposed magnetic field where NEMPI
is known to be excited,
strong density stratification plays an important role.
Furthermore, there is evidence for
the existence of downflows at the locations of the magnetic structures
in both systems.
However, in our two-layer model the formation of bipolar regions is
still observed for smaller scale separation ratios than what was required
for a turbulent system with an imposed magnetic field where NEMPI was excited.

To arrive at a more definitive conclusion regarding the mechanism of
bipolar structure formation, it would be desirable to measure
the effective magnetic pressure tensors in our two-layer model
and to study its parameter dependency in more details.
This requires to develop an adequate test-field method.
This is a subject of a separate study.


